The paper deals with the configuration space of rectangulations and convex subdivisions of points in the plane, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of flip and rotate operations suggests a connection to discrete and combinatorial geometry (cs.DM), while the study of the diameter of the configuration space relates to computational complexity and graph theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves algorithmic techniques and analysis, which could fall under the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the study of configuration spaces and transformations can have applications in robotics and motion planning, which could fall under the sub-category of robotics (cs.SI).
